04204nam a22005415i 9780520967229DE-B159720190920094934.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190920s2017    cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209672297 a10.1525/97805209672292doi  a(DE-B1597)519879  a(OCoLC)962442147  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aE184.A75bL86 2018 7aSOC0310002bisacsh04a305.8950730794732231 aLung-Amam, Willow, eauthor.10aTrespassers? :bAsian Americans and the Battle for Suburbia /cWillow Lung-Amam. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Landscapes of Difference -- t1. The New Gold Mountain -- t2. A Quality Education for Whom? -- t3. Mainstreaming the Asian Mall -- t4. That "Monster House" Is My Home -- t5. Charting New Suburban Storylines -- tAfterword: Keeping the Dream Alive in Troubled Times -- tAppendix: Methods for Revealing Hidden Suburban Narratives -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeyond the gilded gates of Google, little has been written about the suburban communities of Silicon Valley. Over the past several decades, the region's booming tech economy spurred rapid population growth, increased racial diversity, and prompted an influx of immigration, especially among highly skilled and educated migrants from China, Taiwan, and India. At the same time, the response to these newcomers among long-time neighbors and city officials revealed complex attitudes in even the most well-heeled and diverse communities.  Trespassers? takes an intimate look at the everyday life and politics inside Silicon Valley against a backdrop of these dramatic demographic shifts. At the broadest level, it raises questions about the rights of diverse populations to their own piece of the suburban American Dream. It follows one community over several decades as it transforms from a sleepy rural town to a global gateway and one of the nation's largest Asian American-majority cities. There, it highlights the passionate efforts of Asian Americans to make Silicon Valley their home by investing in local schools, neighborhoods, and shopping centers. It also provides a textured tale of the tensions that emerge over this suburb's changing environment. With vivid storytelling, Trespassers? uncovers suburbia as an increasingly important place for immigrants and minorities to register their claims for equality and inclusion.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aAsian AmericanszCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County) 0aSuburbszCaliforniazSanta Clara Valley (Santa Clara County) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520967229423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780520967229.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066755-4  UC Press eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles